name: Lewis County Health
tweet: There is NO known safe blood lead level. Act early and get your child tested! Blood lead tests are usually recommended for children at 12- and 24-months. Talk to your doctor or health care provider for more information.   https://t.co/LMmAcKkNwX  #NLPPW2020 #leadfreekids  https://t.co/gPeDAn0TyF

name: Lewis County Health
tweet: National Lead Poisoning Prevention Week Message 4:  Lead in soil can be ingested as a result of hand-to-mouth activity that is common for young children—remember to wash your child’s hands after they come in from playing outside.  https://t.co/jnmO4kwcyR  #NLPPW2020 #leadfreekids  https://t.co/me7hHPdyoh

name: Lewis County Health
tweet: National Lead Poisoning Prevention Week Message 3:  You cannot see, taste, or smell lead in drinking water, but you can learn basic information about sources of lead in drinking water and suggestions for reducing exposure!  https://t.co/xU527L3Nhb   #NLPPW2020 #leadfreekids  https://t.co/g1HXlS7t0I

name: Lewis County Health
tweet: Lead exposure is dangerous during early childhood development, particularly for children who crawl! Make sure to take off your shoes when entering the house to prevent bringing lead-contaminated soil in from outside.  https://t.co/AYexJIWC0Z  #NLPPW2020 #leadfreekids

name: Lewis County Health
tweet: Many homes built before 1978 contain lead paint. When lead paint gets old, it can start peeling and become a hazard. Find out more! #NLPPW2020 #leadfreekids  https://t.co/5uHcwSQqlF

name: Lewis County Health
tweet: Say BOO to the flu by getting your family vaccinated. It can take up to two weeks for the flu vaccine to fully kick in, so it’s best to get the flu vaccine before Halloween.  More tips here:  https://t.co/KGmSy8MF64   #FluBeforeBoo  https://t.co/gEXOvhn6AP
